4. Execution Pipeline
INPUT
 ↓
Semantic Encoding          (language basis)
 ↓
Structural Modeling         (math basis)
 ↓
Constraint Filtering        (science / empirical basis)
 ↓
Domain Routing              (Conductor selects minimum lens set)
 ↓
Multi-Domain Interpretation (parallel projection across active domains)
 ↓
Action Synthesis            (cross-domain agreement → ranked actions)
 ↓
Confidence Scoring          (HIGH / MEDIUM / LOW / WEAK)
 ↓
Memory Compression          (EchoFrame → delta → ledger append)
 
Pipeline Stage Definitions
Semantic Encoding  →  applies language-basis transforms: define (Sanskrit-style), map (Hebrew-style), name (German compound), compress (Arabic density), narrate (Persian resonance).
Structural Modeling  →  applies math-basis transforms: algebraic invariant check, graph construction, calculus trend detection, probability estimation, information-theoretic compression, linear algebra vectorization.
Constraint Filtering  →  applies empirical basis: chemistry (what combines), physics (what accumulates or redistributes), biology (what adapts or fails).
Domain Routing  →  Conductor daemon selects the minimum domain subset. See Section 5.
Multi-Domain Interpretation  →  each active domain generates one interpretation object: { domain, summary, signal, evidence }.
Action Synthesis  →  cross-domain agreement produces ranked action list. See Section 7.
Confidence Scoring  →  HIGH (≥2 domains, strong agreement), MEDIUM (mixed), LOW (sparse), WEAK (single domain, no corroboration).
Memory Compression (EchoFrame)  →  snapshot → delta → pattern → distilled memory entry. Append-only. Reversible.
 
5. Domain Routing Engine
 
Goal: select the minimum sufficient domain set. Selection error is more dangerous than selection omission — overfitting domains produces noise.
 
Routing Heuristics
